Comment::::<div class="com_user_text">
                            The Modi govt's decision to go with the land-bill this early into their tenure is a smart move for the long run. While this acquisition issue and farmer suicides will certainly be used as a Sanjeevani by the congress, it will not serve as a strong enough wedge issue by the time of the next elections are due. There is a lot of hysteria and misunderstanding surrounding the new land-bill and 4 years is a long enough time for the BJP to counter and correct the negative perceptions that surface. I don't think the "nuclear deal" and "land bill" can be compared. The nuclear deal was a lot less contentious than the present land-bill. Plus the negative consequences of a "nuclear meltdown" are not the sort of things that the layman can imagine with clarity. The land-bill deals with a lot more tangible and real factors which will make for a more stronger and sustained emotive response. The BJP will have to start working on their communication strategy, if they are to think of retaining the majority that they have won this time around. Hopefully, the economy and manufacturing will pick up by then and people, especially the farmer class will be able to reap some of its benifits--either by new jobs in the industry or higher yield etc. The congress has to start differentiating itself from the AAP and CPI, especially in terms of its economic policies. This "leftist" and "anti-business" line that Rahul is toeing will stop reaping dividends after a point. There is a reason why the Communist party had been withering away; the bulk of it had to do with the fact that there economic policies were not conducive for job-creation. If the congress doesn't start projecting their "centrist" credentials by election-time, they are not going to be able to make a significant comeback.
