Author::::<a href="http://social.ndtv.com/groups.php?id=688670" target="_blank">brogo</a>

Comment::::<div class="com_user_text">
                            The main reason this is being done is missed. Contrary to the popular opinion, this is not to create direct jobs but indirect jobs. The government is eyeing the use of land, not for any of the giving to industry reasons that you think. This would directly impede them being elected for the next decade if they did so and they are not fools. <br/><br/>
The main reason is to build energy sector plants, specifically nuclear reactors. The script is written, we have the support of the us for technology, the uranium negotiated with australia and canada. Only stop is nuclear plants.<br/><br/>
The biggest actor against this included Greenpeace, which has been brought to reins. The main cause for concern is for a reactor, you need it near a good water source and accessible by road (but further away from big cities). Further, reactors take a long time to complete and a 5 yr time frame is not sufficient. Good water sources are usually directly correlated with fertile land. Irrigation projects will be a side-effect of any nuclear project since they can be achieved with relative ease. This is why the govt keeps saying irrigation projects.<br/><br/>
Most barren land is not near a water source and hence the need for acquisition. The farmers will give land for irrigation but not for reactors. With no reactors we will be obliterated in the industrial front. <br/><br/>
I am not making a case for or against the government but note that the changes proposed do not allow for non-government holding of the land. On the lease, it is unsustainable since the lease amount would have to be determined by a complex array of things and if one of the farmers who owns the center part of the reactor were to withdraw his lease, what would you do ?
